{
  "document_id": "prov-20",
  "title": "Proverbs 20",
  "type": "study-bible",
  "translation": "Oxford",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-heading-21",
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "21"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-2",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 2,
      "text": "The dread anger of a king is like the growling of a lion; anyone who provokes him to anger forfeits life itself."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-3",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "2 : King's anger, see 19.12n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 2,
      "verse_end": 2
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-3",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 3,
      "text": "It is honorable to refrain from strife, but every fool is quick to quarrel."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-4",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 4,
      "text": "The lazy person does not plow in season; harvest comes, and there is nothing to be found."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-4",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "4 : , see 6.9–11n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 4,
      "verse_end": 4
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-5",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 5,
      "text": "The purposes in the human mind are like deep water, but the intelligent will draw them out."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-5",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "5 : ee 18.4n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 5,
      "verse_end": 5
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-6",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 6,
      "text": "Many proclaim themselves loyal, but who can find one worthy of trust?"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-6",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "6 : , a rhetorical question that suggests trustworthy people are few and far between (cf. 31.10; Eccl 7.24).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 6,
      "verse_end": 6
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-7",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 7,
      "text": "The righteous walk in integrity— happy are the children who follow them!"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-7",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "7 : See 13.22.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 7,
      "verse_end": 7
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-8",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 8,
      "text": "A king who sits on the throne of judgment winnows all evil with his eyes."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-8",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "8 : , to throw threshed grain into the air with a wooden shovel or fork so the wind can separate its components— grain, straw, chaff—by weight (Ps 1.4; Isa 41.15–16).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 8,
      "verse_end": 8
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-9",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 9,
      "text": "Who can say, “I have made my heart clean; I am pure from my sin”?"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-10",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 10,
      "text": "Diverse weights and diverse measures are both alike an abomination to the Lord."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-9",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "10 : , see 11.1n.; cf. v. 23. , see 3.32n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 10,
      "verse_end": 10
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-11",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 11,
      "text": "Even children make themselves known by their acts, by whether what they do is pure and right."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-12",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 12,
      "text": "The hearing ear and the seeing eye— the Lord has made them both."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-13",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 13,
      "text": "Do not love sleep, or else you will come to poverty; open your eyes, and you will have plenty of bread."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-10",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "13 : , see 6.9–11n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 13,
      "verse_end": 13
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-14",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 14,
      "text": "“Bad, bad,” says the buyer, then goes away and boasts."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-11",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "14 : A haggler dismisses a product to lower its price, and then boasts about his cunning (cf. 25.14; 27.2).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 14,
      "verse_end": 14
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-15",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 15,
      "text": "There is gold, and abundance of costly stones; but the lips informed by knowledge are a precious jewel."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-12",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "15 : , see 2.4n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 15,
      "verse_end": 15
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-16",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 16,
      "text": "Take the garment of one who has given surety for a stranger; seize the pledge given as surety for foreigners."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-13",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "16 : , see 6.1–5n.; cf. 27.13.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 16,
      "verse_end": 16
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-17",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 17,
      "text": "Bread gained by deceit is sweet, but afterward the mouth will be full of gravel."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-14",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "17 : , i.e., stolen food or a steady diet of dishonesty; cf. 9.17; 8.18; 26.22.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 17,
      "verse_end": 17
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-18",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 18,
      "text": "Plans are established by taking advice; wage war by following wise guidance."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-15",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "18 : See 11.14n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 18,
      "verse_end": 18
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-19",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 19,
      "text": "A gossip reveals secrets; therefore do not associate with a babbler."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-16",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "19 : , see 16.28n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 19,
      "verse_end": 19
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-20",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 20,
      "text": "If you curse father or mother, your lamp will go out in utter darkness."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-17",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "20 : Cursing parents was a capital offense; see Ex 21.17; Lev 20.9; cf. Deut 27.16. , see 13.9n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 20,
      "verse_end": 20
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-21",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 21,
      "text": "An estate quickly acquired in the beginning will not be blessed in the end."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-18",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "21 : , i.e., inalienable family property wrongfully seized from another (e.g., 1 Kings 21) or claimed prematurely; see 1.18–19n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 21,
      "verse_end": 21
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-22",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 22,
      "text": "Do not say, “I will repay evil”; wait for the Lord, and he will help you."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-19",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "22 : Even pondering revenge is forbidden; retribution belongs to God. See 24.29; cf. Lev 19.18; Ex 23.4; Rom 12.20–21.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 22,
      "verse_end": 22
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-23",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 23,
      "text": "Differing weights are an abomination to the Lord, and false scales are not good."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-20",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "23 : See v. 10; 11.1n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 23,
      "verse_end": 23
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-24",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 24,
      "text": "All our steps are ordered by the Lord; how then can we understand our own ways?"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-21",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "24 : See 16.1,3–4, 9; 21.30–31.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 24,
      "verse_end": 24
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-25",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 25,
      "text": "It is a snare for one to say rashly, “It is holy,” and begin to reflect only after making a vow."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-22",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "25 : , a vow that consecrates a treasured item to God and offers it to the temple. Vows must be paid (cf. Num 30.3; Deut 23.22–24; Ps 50.14; Eccl 4.17–5.5; Sir 18.22–23).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 25,
      "verse_end": 25
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-26",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 26,
      "text": "A wise king winnows the wicked, and drives the wheel over them."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-23",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "26 : See v. 8. , the heavy wheel or drum rolled over grain to thresh it (Isa 28.27).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 26,
      "verse_end": 26
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-27",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 27,
      "text": "The human spirit is the lamp of the Lord, searching every inmost part."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-24",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "27 : , see 13.9n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 27,
      "verse_end": 27
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-28",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 28,
      "text": "Loyalty and faithfulness preserve the king, and his throne is upheld by righteousness."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-25",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "28 : See 16.12–13n.; 25.5; 29.14.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 28,
      "verse_end": 28
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-29",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 29,
      "text": "The glory of youths is their strength, but the beauty of the aged is their gray hair."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-26",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "29 : See 16.31.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 29,
      "verse_end": 29
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-30",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 30,
      "text": "Blows that wound cleanse away evil; beatings make clean the innermost parts."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-1",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "10.1–22.16: The proverbs of Solomon. Comprised predominantly of two-line proverbs, the oldest section of Proverbs can be divided into 10.1–15.33, which features antithetical proverbs, and 16.1–22.16, which includes a mix of proverbial forms.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 30
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-20-h1kj-27",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "30 : Physical discipline was part of ancient Near Eastern education; see 10.13n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 20
      },
      "verse_start": 30,
      "verse_end": 30
    }
  ]
}